Apply fundamental theorem of calculus
$$
\begin{aligned}
\lim _{x \rightarrow 0} \frac{x^2-\int_0^{x^2} e^{-y^2} d y}{x^6} & =\lim _{x \rightarrow 0} \frac{2 x-2 x e^{-x^4}}{6 x^5}=\lim _{x \rightarrow 0} \frac{1}{3}\left(\frac{1-e^{-x^4}}{x^4}\right)=\lim _{y \rightarrow 0} \frac{1}{3}\left(\frac{1-e^{-y}}{y}\right) \\
& =\lim _{y \rightarrow 0} \frac{1}{3} e^{-y}=\frac{1}{3} e^{-0}=\frac{1}{3}
\end{aligned}
$$

Hence, $a=1, b=3 \Rightarrow a+b=4$

$\ln A=\lim _{x \rightarrow 0} \frac{1}{\sin ^{-1} n x} \ln (1+\arctan (\arcsin x)+\arctan (\arcsin 2 x)+\ldots+\arctan (\arcsin n x))$
$$
\begin{aligned}
& =\lim _{x \rightarrow 0} \frac{1}{n x}(\arctan (\arcsin x)+\arctan (\arcsin 2 x)+\ldots \ldots+\arctan (\arcsin n x)) \\
& =\frac{1}{n}(1+2+3+\ldots \ldots+n)=\frac{n+1}{2}
\end{aligned}
$$

Put $n=11 \Rightarrow \ln A=6$
